node.text:
This week, instead of sipping, we’re snacking. Contributing editor Sean Flynn (@travelingnewyorker) is back in Riviera Nayarit, Mexico at One&Only Mandarina (@oomandarina) cooking with Executive Chef Olivier Deboise (@olideboise). Chef’s Fire-Roasted Gratinated Oysters are sure to be a hit at your next summer party.
.
Ingredients:
½ dozen oysters
1 ½ oz butter
1 ½ oz aged goat cheddar
½ tsp shallots, diced
½ tsp Serrano chili, chopped
½ tsp epazote, julienned
Zest of 1 lemon
Zest of 1 lime 
.
Top each oyster with ¼ oz of butter and divide the chopped ingredients, lemon zest, and lime zest among the oysters. Top with grated aged goat cheddar. Grill over a medium to low flame for three to four minutes and brûlée for one and a half minutes. Serve hot.

node.title: These Fire-Roasted Oysters Are the Perfect Summer Appetizer

node.text: Next up on Sipping With, Sean (@travelingnewyorker) visits One&Only Mandarina (@oomandarina) in beautiful Riviera Nayarit, Mexico, where Mixologist Ivan Aguilar shows us how to make one of his favorite cocktails. Of course, no trip to Mexico is complete without tequila, so naturally, that’s our spirit of choice for this episode. In fact, Ivan shows us that tequila can be used to add a twist to cocktails that traditionally use other liquors. We hope you’ll follow along and sip with us at home. Cheers!

node.title: Calling All Tequila Lovers, This Cocktail Could Become Your New Favorite

node.text: On the latest episode of Sipping With, Sean (@travelingnewyorker) heads to his hometown of Buffalo, New York to learn how to make three different summertime cocktails from head bartender at Lloyd Taco Factory (@lloydtacofactory), Jon Wheelock (@jwheels1). We won't give away what they're making, but we will say, if gin is your spirit of choice, you're in for a treat. We hope you’ll follow along and sip with us at home. Cheers!

node.title: Elevate Your Next Summer Get-together With These Cocktail Recipes

node.text: Introducing Sipping With, a new series hosted by Contributing Editor Sean Flynn (@travelingnewyorker), who’s taking us behind the bar at world-renowned restaurants, hotels, and resorts to see how the best in the business craft specialty cocktails. Cheers!

node.text: In this new video series, Walk With T+L, we'll be taking you on some of the best walking tours across the globe. On this episode: the island of Amorgos, Greece. Luckily, there are more than 200 inhabited islands in Greece, meaning you can get all of the beauty and none the crowds on some of the lesser-known islands, like Amorgos. Come along! node.title: This Greek Island Has All of the Beauty and None of the Crowds

node.text: In this new video series, Walk With T+L, we'll be taking you on some of the best walking tours across the globe. On this episode: Paris, France. A city that needs no introduction, Paris may as well be synonymous with food, culture, fashion, and architecture. Despite being a bucket-list destination for millions of people, the French capital still holds plenty of hidden secrets beyond the Eiffel Tower and world-class museums. Join us on this walking tour to see for yourself. Tour by @walkstours

node.title: Jet Off to Paris From the Comfort of Your Home on This Virtual Walking Tour

These stories will give insight into the historic work of the Underground Railroad and the experiences of the individuals who traveled it in hopes of escaping slavery. Come along. Tour by @manumissiontour

node.text:
This week on Behind the Views: Sameer Ahmed (@sameer.design). Sameer’s original reason for buying a camera didn’t have anything to do with travel — he just wanted take photos at his brother’s wedding. “I wanted to test the camera, so I ventured out and captured some shots of the Edmonton skyline at sunset,” he recently shared with T+L. “After spending a few hours watching Lightroom tutorials and messing around with different editing tools, I was very pleased with the results. Since then, I’ve been hooked.”
.
When asked about his approach to travel photography, he says, “I usually plan my itinerary a few days in advance, track the weather forecast, and shoot during sunrise and sunset. My main priority is to make good use out of the day and hit prime spots when the light is at its best.”
.
Sameer’s advice for travel photographers: “I’d say slow down, enjoy the location and its culture, and take your time. Sometimes when you travel for photography it can start to feel exhausting, as you spend hours trying to get the perfect shot. Also, it's always fun to travel with some photographer buddies to make your trips more exciting.”
.
In Sameer’s go-to camera bag you’ll find: a Sony A7R3 camera, Sony 16-35 F2.8 and Sony 24-105 F4 lenses, a DJI Mavic Air 2 drone, and ND Filters.
.
All photos by @sameer.design

This week, instead of sipping, we’re snacking. Contributing editor Sean Flynn (@travelingnewyorker) is back in Riviera Nayarit, Mexico at One&Only Mandarina (@oomandarina) cooking with Executive Chef Olivier Deboise (@olideboise). Chef’s Fire-Roasted Gratinated Oysters are sure to be a hit at your next summer party.
.
Ingredients:
½ dozen oysters
1 ½ oz butter
1 ½ oz aged goat cheddar
½ tsp shallots, diced
½ tsp Serrano chili, chopped
½ tsp epazote, julienned
Zest of 1 lemon
Zest of 1 lime 
.
Top each oyster with ¼ oz of butter and divide the chopped ingredients, lemon zest, and lime zest among the oysters. Top with grated aged goat cheddar. Grill over a medium to low flame for three to four minutes and brûlée for one and a half minutes. Serve hot.
